name: debmans
description:
`debmans` is a tool to extract documentation (currently manpages) from
Debian packages and transform them into HTML for viewing with a normal
web browser.
contribution_justification:
https://debmans.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing.html
pull requests at https://gitlab.com/anarcat/debmans/merge_requests/new
license_location_justification: https://gitlab.com/anarcat/debmans/blob/master/LICENSE.rst
floss_license_justification: https://debmans.readthedocs.io/en/latest/license.html The AGPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The AGPL-3.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
repo_public_justification: https://gitlab.com/anarcat/debmans/
release_notes_justification: will be part of the debian changelog once releases start and packaging is done.
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: https://debmans.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing.html#issues-feature-requests-and-security says to use email with OpenPGP.
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: https://debmans.readthedocs.io/en/latest/contributing.html#issues-feature-requests-and-security - encrypted OpenPGP emails supported and confidential gitlab issues can be used.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: no security issues reported so far, but they will be dealt with promptly.
test_invocation_justification: `python setup.py test` was configured to call pytest correctly.
warnings_justification: there are no compiled files, but we should recommend and hook into pyflakes in the test suite.
warnings_fixed_justification: that said, files are generally PEP8-clean.
know_common_errors_justification:
debmans uses the least privilege approach: it doesn't require `root` access to run. it accesses the Debian mirror readonly and only writes to a specific directory. the package archive is nevertheless "trusted" in that it is assumed that the data in the debian packages is valid, considering it is otherwise ran as root on all Debian systems... the commandline is made to be as intuitive and usable as possible, following POLA.

there is currently a limited web interface which could provide ways to do XSS and that needs to be verified. otherwise the security impact of the site is curently low.
delivery_mitm_justification: source code available through HTTPS, git release tags will be signed, final service will run on HTTPS.
delivery_unsigned_justification: checksums are not fetched over the network: the archive is checked locally
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: no known security issues thus far.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: all critical security issues will be promptly fixed
dynamic_analysis_justification: Debmans is written in Python and is therefore less vulnerable to this sort of issues. It does, however, use third-party libraries (e.g. `python-apt`) that have parts written in C/C++ that may be vulnerable, but this falls out of the scope of this audit.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: there are some runtime assert statements.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: any such vulnerability would of course be promptly fixed.
general_comments: Project was abandoned in the favor of debiman.
discussion_justification:
Gitlab issues, Debian wiki
https://gitlab.com/anarcat/debmans/issues/new
https://wiki.debian.org/manpages.debian.org
no_leaked_credentials_justification: no private credentials are necessary to operate this, short of SSH keys to deploy on a server, which are not part of the repository.
crypto_used_network_justification: currently doesn't use the network. when virtual hosts are configured, they will use HTTPS.
hardened_site_justification: One or more of the required security hardening headers is missing. X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: this will be implemented through a Debian package eventually.
build_reproducible_justification: it is assumed to be reproducible, being python, but should be verified.

name: dash
description: C++ Template Library for Distributed Data Structures with Support for Hierarchical Locality for HPC and Data-Driven Science
contribution_justification: https://github.com/dash-project/dash/blob/development/CONTRIBUTING.md
license_location_justification:
LICENSE file in root directory of the distribution.
https://github.com/dash-project/dash/blob/development/COPYING.md
floss_license_justification:
Redistribution and use in source and binary forms, with or without modification, are permitted.
The license will soon be replaced by GPL 3-clause.

https://github.com/dash-project/dash/blob/development/LICENSE The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: The BSD-3-Clause license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification:
Distribution notes:
- https://github.com/dash-project/dash/blob/development/README.md
User documentation included in source distribution:
- https://dash.readthedocs.io/en/latest
Community wiki:
- http://doc.dash-project.org
documentation_interface_justification:
API is documented via Doxygen. Documentation is automatically generated and published for every change on the release branches.

https://codedocs.xyz/dash-project/dash/
build_justification: Two build systems are provided, along with automated installation scripts for common configurations.
build_common_tools_justification:
DASH distributions provide two build systems:
- Makefiles for minimal builds (some plugins and optimizations unavailable)
- CMake build system following official guidelines as closely as possible, but also including custom CMake modules to meet requirements for installations on HPC clusters
build_floss_tools_justification: DASH supports a few non-free libraries like Intel MKL, but also many FLOSS alternatives to achieve the same features, like OpenBLAS or ATLAS.
test_justification:
Comprehensive unit test suites based on googletest and continuous integration scripts.
The source distribution contains test suites, performance profiling tools and debugging utilities.
test_invocation_justification: Continuous integration with test runs for multiple build configurations can be started by running 'dash/scripts/dash-ci.sh'
test_most_justification: An rcov / gcov build is provided in the CMake build system and monitored for pull requests.
warnings_justification:
The build configurations use the most restrictive compiler flags available such as `-Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic`.
CppCheck and cpplint are common practice among contributors and will soon be added in CI.
static_analysis_justification: Static code analysis is performed based on scan-build provided by the LLVM project and is also available to users by executing the script build.analyze.sh
general_comments:
Summary
-------

Exascale systems are scheduled to become available in 2018-2020 and will be
characterized by extreme scale and a multilevel hierarchical organization.

Efficient and productive programming of these systems will be a challenge,
especially in the context of data-intensive applications. Adopting the 
promising notion of Partitioned Global Address Space (PGAS) programming the
DASH project develops a data-structure oriented C++ template library that
provides hierarchical PGAS-like abstractions for important data containers
(multidimensional arrays, lists, hash tables, etc.) and allows a developer
to control (and explicitly take advantage of) the hierarchical data layout
of global data structures.

In contrast to other PGAS approaches such as UPC, DASH does not propose a
new language or require compiler support to realize global address space 
semantics. Instead, operator overloading and other advanced C++ features
are used to provide the semantics of data residing in a global and
hierarchically partitioned address space based on a runtime system with
one-sided messaging primitives provided by MPI or GASNet.

As such, DASH can co-exist with parallel programming models already in
widespread use (like MPI) and developers can take advantage of DASH by
incrementally replacing existing data structures with the implementation
provided by DASH. Efficient I/O directly to and from the hierarchical
structures and DASH-optimized algorithms such as map-reduce are also part
of the project. Two applications from molecular dynamics and geoscience
are driving the project and are adapted to use DASH.


Funding
-------

DASH is funded by the German Research Foundation (DFG) under the priority
programme "Software for Exascale Computing - SPPEXA" (2013-2018).
test_continuous_integration_justificatio:
Several CI systems are used at different stages in development- and release processes.
DASH currently uses TravisCI and CircleCI as public infrastructures for continuous integration (3 build configurations x 3 test setups x 2 test environments).

https://travis-ci.org/dash-project/dash
https://circleci.com/gh/dash-project/dash

The most comprehensive tests are executed on internal servers.
Test results from long-running (12h+) system tests and performance monitoring results from the non-public setups will soon be automatically published.
discussion_justification:
Issue tracking:
- https://github.com/dash-project/dash/issues
Support:
- support@dash-project.org
Developer mailing list:
- team@dash-project.org
IRC channel:
- #dash-project  / irc.freenode.net
